segments.text: No, football was, I guess Aggies have always been wild about football, as everybody is in Texas, I think.
And, you know, we really loved football, and knowing a lot of the players, because as a
freshman, that was the first time that the football players had lived in the outfits that year of 1941.
Prior to that, they had all lived in dorm 12
or a athletic dormitory where they were all together.
But this year was the first time they tried an experiment of putting them all back in there.
Did you have any athletes in your outfit?
No, none.
Well, we had one, Freddie Walters.
You know Freddie?
He's over there.
I think he's still with the bank.
Freddie was in our outfit.
He was a year ahead of me.
And I believe that was the only one we had in our outfit.
All right.
On a game day, had classes on Saturday morning, and then did you all march in?
Yes.
The Corps did march in?
Well, wait a minute.
Let's see.
I'm getting to it.
No, we didn't march in.
Uh-uh.
No.
So you just went on your own.
That's right.
But in uniform.
When I say we didn't march in,
we usually went in behind the band.
But, I mean, there was no, not like they do now and really have a march in.
No, we just went on our own.
What were some memorable moments for you of that fall's football season?
Well...
I don't know.
I just...
Did you go to some out-of-town games?
Oh yes, yes.
Well, we had a court trip to, let's see, my freshman year we had a court trip to Dallas and Fort Worth.
It seemed like- Now normally didn't go to
Oh, wait a minute.
No, one year we went, I'm trying to think, we were sophomores when we went to Fort Worth.
I guess we went to Dallas as freshmen.
Dallas and Houston?
And Houston.
Yeah, yeah.
The Houston trip was, let's see.
Well, anyway, let's go back to a few days before the Houston game, the Rice game.
We had some adventurous freshmen who decided they'd steal Sammy the Rice Owl.
And they did.
They got down there and they got Sammy from the
trophy case and got outside the building, but they didn't get off campus.
They were caught.
And there was a picture, I believe, in the Post.
It might have been the Chronicle.
I think it was
They caught these Aggies, and they shaved their heads, with the exception of four of them, and they left an R, an I, C, E. And they had them all down on all fours.
And they took their picture.
And I believe it was in the Houston Post.
I'm not sure.
But anyway, they get back to College Station.
the paper comes out and anyway the Bulls office figures we're going to have these guys nailed.
Well, they didn't count on the ingenuity of some Aggies, so every outfit we drew straws
One boy in every outfit had to have his head shaved.
So they did, and as far as I know, Joe Davis, who was just an assistant at that time, they never caught anybody.
for pulling the steel.
Did you students know who the two guilty parties, the four guilty parties?
I knew two of them.
But you all knew who they were?
Oh yes, oh yes.
Let's see, how did, when you went on a court trip, how did that first year, how did you get there?
By some, or any way you could.
But did you hitchhike?
Oh yes, yes.
Describe how an Aggie hitchhiked in that era.
What'd you wear?
Where'd you catch the ride?
Well, we usually caught out right up there at, which was East Gate.
And there's very, very definite strict rules about hitchhiking.
You'd go out and you'd get in line.
You'd put on a little suitcase or whatever and
It might be a long line, but the ones that were there first went out first, and this had absolutely nothing to do with whether you were a senior freshman or whatever.
This was who was there first.
And sometimes they wouldn't take a ride.
Maybe the ride would just be to Hearn, and the guy would say, no thanks, I don't want that.
Well, then the next guy got a choice, and so on and so forth.

And speaking of that, one time I remember taking the line to go towards, we were going to San Antonio, and the line towards Austin was so long that I don't think I'd ever gotten out that a fella stopped and said, he's going to Caldwell.
Nobody wanted to ride to Caldwell, so another fella and I took the ride to Caldwell.
Then when we got to Caldwell, we caught right north to, well, we ended up in Taylor.
I've forgotten, Cameron.
We went up to Cameron and then over to Taylor.
And by this time, it's the Friday night football game.
It's just over in Taylor.
So you can see it took us a little while to get there.
and there were some girls driving around in the car, and we got to talking to them.
They stopped, and we finally talked them into, if we'd buy them two gallons of gas, would they drive us down to Austin?
And they did.
So anyway, but the Corps trips, we had great times.
I know
The year we went to Fort Worth, God, there must have been 10 of us in that room.
I don't know whose room it was, but it was just a place to lay down and sleep.
That was the year that we had to publicly give back the Horned Frog flag.
And we had a couple of boys that during the game went up that flagpole and took that pennant loose and came back down and got away without being caught.
Now, you know, if I don't know if you're familiar with the stadium at that time, but the flagpole was at the north end and the play, everything was going on down at the

south end at that time and it was rather tense and these two guys were up that pole and had that deal and were getting ready to come down before anybody really noticed that they were there before the crowd turned around and by the time they hit the ground they were gone and anyway they had to make a presentation back to
Did you ever have a bad experience as an Aggie hitchhiker?
I'm going to answer this like you don't want to hear, but I say no.
I've not had a single negative report yet.
Did you have any humorous events while hitchhiking?
Goofy?
Well, I...
I had a very embarrassing event one time, and a fellow and I had caught a ride.
And by the way, this was to Caldwell again.
And so happened the gentleman we caught a ride with was a preacher.
a boy I was with, nice, I mean, true blue kind of a friend and so on and so forth, but a rather raucous, rough type fella.
And his language was really pretty bad and the preacher took him to task and gave him quite a

quite a little sermon which was well deserved well deserved but it was still embarrassing it was still embarrassing but anyway that's a but all right then back to uh football that year um let's see this is that's the year that the university of texas
was hoping to go to the Rose Bowl.
No, no, no, no, it was the, that was in 39 that A&M was, 41, 40 when A&M was going to the Rose Bowl.
40, all right, then 41.
41, we won the conference, but we lost to Texas.
Yes, yes.
They beat us 20-something to 27 to nothing there at Caulfield.
And do you remember that game?
No, because I didn't see that game.
Oh, you were home?
Yes.
How, normally, particularly your first year, when did you go home, go back home first?
That was the first time I went home.
Okay.
And how'd you get back and forth?
I, I hitchhiked home, and the reason I went home was it was a four-day holiday.
And in order to stay till the last minute at home, I went back on a train.
The only time I think I ever went anywhere up there that wasn't hitchhiking or later on I had an old car that I had bought from working in Laredo.
But I rode that train to
Milano Junction.
And then we had to get off the train and wait there in that old station.
And then another train came through and you got on that and rode down into College Station.
But other than that, I had
Working in Laredo, I had saved up a little bit of money, and I'd boughten, boughten, I had bought a car.
I'd paid, let's see, I think, I think I paid 92 or 93 dollars for that.
And what year was that?
Well, this was in, this was in
40 or 41 that I bought it.
And it was a 32 Ford.
But I think I paid about $90, something like that.
But you didn't bring it to the campus?
No, not when I was a freshman.
I took it up there later as a sophomore.
And
I didn't have it too long.
I mean, we had one of those freezes come through where we were playing football, touch football that afternoon in shorts.
And that night one of those blue norther
came in and I had no antifreeze or anything in that thing and the next morning when I went out I mean there was rivulets of ice where the head had broken on that.
Anyway, I think I got about $20 for that thing salvaged.
But anyway, I got a big kick out of that
having that car because Buck was running, Buck Weiris was running Aggieland that year.
As a freshman, Curly Bryant was the head of the Aggieland Orchestra and Buck played the drums in it.
But as a sophomore, Buck was heading it up and I went two or three different places with him on
and they'd have a date to play, and I'd take about four of them in my car, and they'd pay the gasoline and my meals and get me into the dance free, you know, and so on and so forth.
So I enjoyed that.
Now, don't have any information about the Aggieland Orchestra.
You don't?
So please describe it as much as you can.
Oh, let me tell you, they were great.
I'm telling you, they were really great.
The...
They had, well, and we had something to judge them by, too, because we had some great bands come to the campus.
Jan Garber came, Jimmy Lunsford, Skinny Ennis.
They were great.
And we liked to get black bands down there for one reason mainly.
They couldn't get any pickup musicians.

Now, when Skinny Ennis came, you see, he'd stop in Dallas, he'd bring himself, and he had a trombone player that most people knew, and a couple of others, and he'd bring about four of his regular band.
And then he'd stop in Dallas and get some pickup musicians and come on down, you see.
But if you got a black band,
they had to come pretty well intact.
And Jimmy Lunsford had a great band at that time.
If you remember the song Blues in the Night, well Lunsford had a record that had Blues in the Night on both sides of it, and he had the premier arrangement of that.
But anyway, getting back to the Aggieland Orchestra,
they had a piano man named Dinkle Webb.
And one of our classmates, Murphy, Bill Murphy from Paris, Texas, played sax.
Don Hackney from over at
I can't think of the name of the town.
Where's the Crown Colony Golf Course?
Lufkin.
He was, he's retired.
He was head of Temple.
Temple Industry.
Yeah.
And he played clarinet and was a heck of a clarinet player.
And Buck played the drums.
I can't remember.
And they did what we would now call big band music.
Oh, yes, yes.
Yeah, they had about, it was about a 10-piece, 10 or 12-piece orchestra.
And they played all around, or dances at different schools and everything.
And at that time, there was a radio program that came on on Sunday nights out of New York.
called the Fitch Bandwagon.
And they had, they featured new bands and things like that.
And they got the Aggieland Orchestra, paid their expenses and everything to come to New York and play on the Fitch Bandwagon.
And they were great.
And what did you all do that night?
Listened.
Just listened.
Yeah, no, they was a, they were great.
I wish, I wish Buck was living.
Buck could tell you more stories about
And they were all students.
Oh, yes.
And they got, for that era, they got a good bit of money.
They would make a little bit of spending money?
Yes.
When you say good bit of money, you know...

nothing today absolutely actually for the trip to new york they got their expenses that's all and but the the just think of the pride of that something like that where did they practice mostly i guess it's over in sebasa okay and did they have distinctive aggie band uniforms when they when they were the agulha they played the
For the most part, they'd wear a tuxedo.
Their tuxedos?
Yeah.
And their name was the Aggieland?
The Aggieland Orchestra.
As far as you know, when was it organized?
Seems like there was a fella.
The earliest one, to my knowledge, was a fella named Little John, I believe.
And after him, I think,
then was Curly Bryant, and then Buck.
So, late 30s?
I would guess that's probably right.
It could have been...
I'm really... Let's see.
No, I'd say early to middle 30s.
I'd say middle 30s.
And then it ceases with the war.
Let's say it was interrupted.
Oh, did they recreate it?
Yes.
What's his name...
And Joe Haney, after the war, and how long after the war, I don't know when they recreated the Aggieland, but they were, Joe Haney was bandmaster and he had a young gentleman
under him named Brewster.
Brewster.
Nice, nice young man.
Now, were all the members in your day, were all the members of the Aggieland Orchestra also in the Aggie marching band?
I'm trying to think.
No.
No, they weren't because Buck was never in the band.
That's what I thought.
Murphy was.
I don't think Deagle Webb was.
I don't think Curly Bryant was.
But there was no requirement one way or another.
The Anglin was a separate entity unto itself.
It had no... No faculty advisor?
No, no, no.
Absolutely nothing.
We had a lot of things at A&M that had no...
you know it was just the thing they did and everybody i i do have to say that there was an amazing amount of uh
self-control on things like that.
They were handled.
I'm sorry to take.
No, no, no, no, no, no.
I'm just checking.
Yeah.
So how much more time we have?
Because I've got the whole afternoon.
The world then changed for your generation and mine on December 7th.
Yes, sir.
Describe as much as you can where you were, what happened that day and the next day for you and your friends.
I was at the dormitory.
For some reason, I don't know, most everybody liked to go to the movie on Sunday afternoon, and I was amongst them.
However, for some reason this Sunday, whether they had something on that,
I didn't like or whether it was too crowded or I don't know, but I didn't go.
I was, I was there.
And just taking it easy.
And all of a sudden somebody stood running out and you heard somebody yelling out in the outside saying, we're at war, we're at war, we're at war.
What in the hell's going on, you know?
And I went down.
Well, they had stopped the movie at Northgate and announced what had taken place.
And at first, we didn't believe it, you know.
But as far as every little thing that took place, everybody was talking at once.
you know, already conjecting what was going to happen, whether they were going to take us into the service immediately or what we were going to do and all this kind of stuff.
And I guess some of the sophomores decided that we better have a little drill or something, so they started marching us around a bit.
It was just something, electricity in the air, that really never went away.
Did the routine change in the dormitory and classes and drills pretty quickly?
Not a whole lot, except people did take the military classes a little more seriously than they had prior to that.
And everybody wanted to be
be sure they got a contract.
You're familiar with what I mean when I say got a contract, okay.
And we, in fact, that sent a lot of us to, OCS probably kept a lot of boys from getting killed if you want to be perfectly frank about it, because when we, after we went into the service,
We were brought back to campus, and then after we were there a certain time, they sent us all off to a basic training.
Didn't have any OCS to send us to immediately after we finished basic training, so they sent us back to A&M.
And then they started pulling us out a few at a time.
And my group was sent back to Fort Sill.
We were in artillery.
Sent back to Fort Sill and assigned to the school troops.
And they were going to take us out a few at a time into the Officer Candidate School.
They only took one bunch out.
And after that, they came in one day and says,
Everybody put your A bag, your B bag, you're shipping out tomorrow at noon.
So we thought we were just going to go across to the OCS area.
And a lot of boys left radios and things like that.
They'd come back and pick them up later.
Well, they came back and picked us up.
They took us to the train station and they sent us to Fort Benning, Georgia.
And through an infantry basic, again,
and then through infantry OCS and then shipped out from there.
So all that delay of this thing, this thing and that delayed everybody being sent into actual action and probably saved a lot of us from being being killed.
All right.
When did you and your colleagues first leave the campus as a part of these changes?
Your second year?
Let's see.
Yes.
The 42-43 year.
Yeah, that's right.
All right.
So during the spring of 1942, you're still taking freshman classes, but life is getting more serious.
Right.
Did some folks start going to church more regularly?
You know...
I didn't really notice.
I usually went, I wasn't a regular attendee, but I went to the Methodist Church at Northgate, and I didn't notice a big increase, to tell you the truth.
Describe the YMCA and what it represented in those days at A&M under Mr. Cashin.
Well, the YMCA was with the exception of the pool room at Wardrop's down at Northgate upstairs over Wardrop's store.
The YMCA was about it as far as recreation other than the
They did have some handball courts down, I think about three or four courts down there behind the gym.
And they had a two or three lane bowling alley in the basement of the Y, which if there wasn't a senior using it or a junior or a sophomore, which was never, you could use it.
They did have a soda fountain there, and it was a nice area, really.
That's where we'd always go to make telephone calls.
That's where the pay phones were.
Did you know Mr. Cashin?
No, I didn't.
Did you know either of the boys, Red or Jim?
Red, yeah.
I knew Red real well, but not
at that time.
I knew Red later on after, well, I guess Red had already started his... NFL officiating?
I don't know if he was in the NFL yet, but he was officiating quite a bit.
I had met Red through Pat Knight.
Pat was, even though he was a bit younger than I, we were very close friends, and I met Red through him, and also, I was always very active in Laredo in the Border Olympics.
I was head of that a couple of years, and Colonel Andy Anderson and I were good friends, and I would, I refereed at the,
Colley Station relays a couple of years.
